04239nam a22006495i 9781474469289DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222004stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744692897 a10.1515/97814744692892doi  a(DE-B1597)615196  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a1262221 aHonderich, Ted, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Consciousness /cTed Honderich. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Anomalous Monism,and the Champion of Mauve -- tChapter Two. The Thinking of Some Neuroscientific Friends -- tChapter Three. Cognitive Science’s Philosophy,and the Union Theory -- tChapter Four. Anti-Individualism v. the Union Theory -- tChapter Five. Consciousness and Humble Truths -- tChapter Six. Seeing Things -- tChapter Seven. Consciousness as the Existence of a World -- tChapter Eight. The Theory Embarked On -- tChapter Nine. The End of Intentionality in Perceptual Consciousness -- tChapter Ten. Reflective and Affective Consciousness -- tChapter Eleven. Spiritualism, Devout Physicalism, Brains in Vats, Neuroscience -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGBS_insertPreviewButtonPopup('ISBN:9780748618422);Is your consciousness neural events in your head? Is it anything in there? On Consciousness offers answers to the question of the very nature of consciousness, and the separate question of how consciousness is related to the brain.It begins with Anomalous Monism, a doctrine seemingly to the effect that mind and brain are one thing with two kinds of properties not lawfully connected. It goes on to consider the thinking of neuroscientists and then functionalists. It reconsiders Honderich's own Union Theory, and the anti-individualism that disconnects the mind from the brain. These doctrines are examined in terms of whether they satisfy our agreed criteria for decent accounts of consciousness.The book leads up to the question: 'What is it like for you to be aware of the room you are in?' The bold new answer is: 'It is for the room in a way to exist'. Such an answer gives rise to analyses of reflective and affective consciousness as well, such as thinking and feeling. On Consciousness respects the most resilient proposition in the history of the philosophy of mind -that consciousness isn't just cells. It also makes all of consciousness a proper subject for science."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aConsciousness. 0aPhilosophy of mind. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147446928940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474469289423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474469289/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK